TY  - JOUR
T1  - Corporate Governance: What can we Learn from Public Governance?
AU  - Benz, Matthias
AU  - Frey, Bruno S.
Y1  - 2007/01/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2007.23463860
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2007.23463860
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 92
EP  - 104
VL  - 32
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In view of recent corporate scandals, we argue that corporate governance can learn from public governance. Institutions devised to control and discipline the behavior of executives in the political sphere can give new insights into how to improve the governance of firms. We discuss proposals in four specific areas: manager compensation, the division of power within firms, rules of succession in top positions, and institutionalized competition in core areas of the corporation.
AB  - In view of recent corporate scandals, we argue that corporate governance can learn from public governance. Institutions devised to control and discipline the behavior of executives in the political sphere can give new insights into how to improve the governance of firms. We discuss proposals in four specific areas: manager compensation, the division of power within firms, rules of succession in top positions, and institutionalized competition in core areas of the corporation.
